\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{ \textbf  {TODO} \par  Talk about how L4 is designed to address these issues. \par Firstly it comes with a concurrent model of computation (this is made precise by the translation to B) which allows for arbitrary interleaving of events. \par It is also friendly to use, containing ontological concepts from the legal domain that people are used to thinking about and working with. \par Discuss the precise roles of these concepts and how the execution of a contract can be viewed abstractly as a process that arises from the interaction between them. \par Mention that the precise operational interpretation of rules in L4 is tightly linked to the translation in B and this was heavily inspired by \cite  {symboleo_model_checking_contracts,eventb_data_sharing_agreements}. \par We view a rule as a wrapper around an event, a deontic (ie permission, obligation or prohibition) and an actor. Our treatment of deontics accounts for the notion of \textit  {compensability}, and is based on \cite  {normative_compliance_guido}. \par Note that the difference is that instead of reasoning about deontics using deontic logic, we provide an \textit  {operational} interpretation for them.  }{3}{section*.4}\protected@file@percent }
