\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{ \textbf  {TODO} \par  Here we should mention that in \cite  {temporal_logic_norms_guido}, the author highlights an issue with using temporal logic to reason about deontics like obligations. We sidestep that issue due to the way we define rules as wrappers around events, and deontics, so that the violation of a rule corresponds directly to whether that event occured or not. \par For instance, a rule of the form ``Party P must do A by D'' is an obligation that is violated if P does not perform A by the deadline D. In this way, we can reason about the violation of obligations by using temporal logic to talk about whether an event occurred or not.  }{5}{section*.6}\protected@file@percent }
